{
  "texts": [
    "Patch-seq is a revolutionary technology that can simultaneously acquire the morphology, electrophysiology, and transcriptome of single cells, which are valuable resources to establish a multimodal atlas.",
    "Patch-seq is a modification of regular patchclamp recording.",
    "It has been applied to record from cultured cells and acute brain sections in vitro [56][57][58]60], and the recorded cells are labeled with dye for subsequent morphological reconstruction.",
    "After electrophysiological recording, most of the cytoplasmic contents are aspirated (generally including the nucleus) and transferred to an individual tube containing a lysis buffer followed by a standard single-cell or single-nucleus RNA-seq protocol (Fig. 1D-G).",
    "This powerful multimodal approach provides valuable resources for advancing our understanding of primate neuroscience.Patch-seq techniques have been successfully implemented in the primate cortex [16,59,61,62,64,90]."
  ]
}